<section class="prose">
  <h1>Privacy</h1>
  <p class="updated">Last updated 11 July 2026</p>

  <p>
    Eleven is built so your conversations belong to you and whoever
    you’re talking to. Not to us, and not to whoever happens to run the
    server. Here’s what that actually means.
  </p>

  <h2>What only you and your recipients can read</h2>
  <p>
    Your device encrypts each message before it’s sent and decrypts it
    when it arrives. The server stores and relays ciphertext it has no
    way to open. That covers:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>the text of every message;</li>
    <li>attachments, including their file names;</li>
    <li>the sender’s name as it’s carried inside each message;</li>
    <li>display names on the member list;</li>
    <li>group names and photos.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What the server can see</h2>
  <p>
    Delivering messages requires knowing a couple of things, though never
    their contents:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Who’s in a chat together.</strong> The server routes
      messages to a chat’s members, so it knows who’s in each one — as
      keys, not names.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>When, and how much.</strong> Message timing and sizes, as
      with any messenger.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    It never sees your messages, your private key, or a chat’s key —
    those only exist on your own devices. Steal the database and you’d
    learn that keys talk to keys. You wouldn’t learn a name, or a word
    anyone said.
  </p>

  <h2>What we don’t do</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>No analytics, no tracking, first-party or third-party.</li>
    <li>No advertising. We don’t sell or share your data.</li>
    <li>No accounts, emails, or phone numbers. You join with a link.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Link previews</h2>
  <p>
    Post a web link and the server fetches that page once, to build a
    preview card: title, description, thumbnail. For that one moment it
    sees the URL. It doesn’t see the rest of your message. This is the
    one exception, and it can be switched off.
  </p>

  <h2>GIF search</h2>
  <p>
    If you search for a GIF, your device asks Giphy directly, so Giphy
    sees the search terms and your network address — never who you are on
    Eleven or who you’re chatting with. Our server sees nothing; the GIF
    you pick is encrypted like any other picture. Don’t use GIF search
    and Giphy never hears from you.
  </p>

  <h2>Notifications</h2>
  <p>
    Push notifications go out encrypted and get decrypted on your own
    device, so neither the notification service nor we can read them.
  </p>

  <h2>Keeping and losing data</h2>
  <p>
    Messages live on the server only as ciphertext, and every chat is its
    own self-contained instance. Saving your sign-in takes one tap, and
    from then on any device can let you back in — the saved copy is
    itself encrypted with a key only your devices hold. Skip that, lose
    your only device, and the keys are gone, along with any history only
    you could read. We never had them to lose.
  </p>

  <h2>Children</h2>
  <p>
    Eleven is meant for families to use together. It collects nothing
    beyond the display name a member picks, and there’s no advertising,
    no feed, and no way for a stranger to reach in.
  </p>

  <h2>Contact</h2>
  <p>
    Questions about privacy? Email
    <a href="mailto:team@elevenmessenger.com">team@elevenmessenger.com</a>.
  </p>

  <p class="fine">
    This page describes how the app works today. It’s meant to be honest,
